article.headline: Boston rallies from 17 down
article.linkText: Davis' jumper puts Celtics over Suns
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- It was the Boston Celtics turn to stage a big comeback against the Phoenix Suns. After blowing a 29-point lead against the Suns three weeks ago, the Celtics rallied from 17 points down in the third quarter and beat Phoenix 104-102 Friday night on Ricky Davis' 20-foot jumper with 2.8 seconds left. Paul Pierce had 27 points, 19 in the second half, for Boston. "The shot was a byproduct of our passing game," said Davis, who was open on the left side and took a pass from Pierce, who had 11 assists. "It feels great. You know, we never give up." This was the first major contribution for Davis since he was recently acquired from Cleveland in a six-player trade. At the time of the deal, the Celtics were highly criticized for getting Davis, a noted problem player with the Cavaliers. But Pierce is happy to have him. "He's scary," Pierce said of Davis, whose sometimes reckless play with Cleveland helped get him traded. "When he starts coming along with us, we're going to be scary." Pierce also liked the Celtics' resiliency. "I think we're playing a little more mentally tough," he said. "We got down and we just didn't give in." Walter McCarty added a season-high 20 points for the Celtics, and Mark Blount had a season-high 16. Davis had his Celtics' high with 14. Shawn Marion topped the Suns with 25 points, while Stephon Marbury scored 18, Penny Hardaway 14, Casey Jacobsen 12 and Joe Johnson 10. "We came back and beat them there (in Boston), then they came back and beat us in our building," said Hardaway, whose 3-pointer with 14 seconds left made it 102-102. "You could feel the momentum changing in the third quarter. We just didn't have anything to show for it. "We did make a shot at the end to tie it, then they came back and made a shot. It's our fault for giving up a lead. We knew better and it cost us." Suns coach Mike D'Antoni called it "a big loss for us." "The air went out of us," he said. "We didn't have the killer instinct when we needed it." Pierce got it going in the third quarter, sparking a 16-0 run with two 3-pointers and hitting another from long range just before the period ended, helping the Celtics tie it at 75 after they had trailed 73-56. Marion scored 13 of the Suns' 19 points in the period, but Phoenix went the final 6:10 without a field goal and committed 10 turnovers in the quarter. Pierce opened the fourth with Boston's first six points and the Celtics led 99-92 with less than 3 minutes remaining. The Suns rallied to even it at 99 on two free throws by Marbury with 30 seconds to go. Mike James and Hardaway then matched 3-pointers before Davis got open and made the game-winning shot. Marbury gave the Suns a 56-45 halftime lead with a desperation 44-footer just before the buzzer. The Suns' defense obviously was geared to try and contain Pierce, the Celtics' leading scorer with an average of 23.7, and limited him to two field goals and eight points in the first half.

Game notes
The Suns traded 6-foot-11 forward Robert Archibald to Orlando for a conditional 2005 second-round draft pick. ... Marbury played with five stitches under his lower lip after colliding with Leandro Barbosa during practice Thursday. ... McCarty, who jumped center to start the game for the smallish Celtics, entered the game as the team's leading 3-point shooter (31-of-64, .484), although he was averaging only 5.5 points.
